description.plain:
Rascal Flatts is a Country music trio from Ohio, who was first formed in 1999. The trio is comprised of Gary LeVox, Jay DeMarcus, and Joe Don Rooney. Throughout their career, the trio have released a total of eleven albums, as well as 37 singles, of which 14 have reached the top spot on the Billboard Hot Country Songs charts.

On January 7, 2020, after twenty years together, the trio announced that they would be disbanding following a farewell tour, which kicks off in June.

songs.title: Life Is a Highway

description.plain:
This is a cover of Tom Cochrane’s 1991 song “Life Is a Highway.” It was popularly featured in the 2006 Disney-Pixar film Cars, as Mack travels with Lightning McQueen down a highway.

After its success, the song was added to Rascal Flatts' album Me And My Gang as a bonus track.

songs.full_title: Bless the Broken Road by Rascal Flatts
songs.title: Bless the Broken Road

description.plain:
“Bless the Broken Road” is the second single released by Rascal Flatts from their album, Feels Like Today. In 2006, the song won the Rascal Flatts a Grammy Award for Best Country Song.

Lyrically, the song describes how getting over a relationship you’ve had in the past can eventually lead you in finding a better love.

songs.full_title: What Hurts The Most by Rascal Flatts
songs.title: What Hurts The Most

description.plain:
“What Hurts The Most” by Rascal Flatts was the first single released from their album Me And My Gang, which eventually topped the charts.

In an interview with writer Jeffrey Steele, he reveals;

the song was originally inspired by losing my father and I just wanted to express something about it – but I ended up changing the meaning and I made it more of a love song, to be more universal.

Gary LeVox, Rascal Flatt’s songwriter and lead singer and Dan Huff, the band’s producer ended up loving the song and produced the song.

In the music video for What Hurts The Most, the music video provides a small story for a girl who suffers the loss of her boyfriend. Her anger in the video is expressed for her father who she blames for making her boyfriend leave, resulting in his demise in a fatal car accident.



Throughout the course of the music video, there are scenes of the band playing, alongside flashbacks of the couple and the girl trying to live on with the loss of her boyfriend.
